{"title_page": "2020 San Diego mayoral election", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|reason=Persistent addition of [[WP:INTREF|unsourced or poorly sourced content]]|small=yes}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2020 San Diego mayoral election\n| country            = \n| flag_image         = Flag of San Diego, California.svg\n| type               = presidential\n| ongoing            = yes\n| previous_election  = 2016 San Diego mayoral election\n| previous_year      = 2016\n| next_election      = 2024 San Diego mayoral election\n| next_year          = 2024\n| election_date      = {{Start date|2020|11|3}}\n| turnout            = \n| 3blank             = Runoff vote\n| 4blank             = Runoff percentage\n| image1             = [[File:AssemblymemberToddGloria.jpg|160x160px]]\n| candidate1         = [[Todd Gloria]]\n| party1             = California Democratic Party\n| 1data1             = \n| 2data1             = \n| image2             = [[File:Barbara Bry Interview.png|160x160px]]\n| candidate2         = [[Barbara Bry]]\n| party2             = California Democratic Party\n| 1data2             = \n| 2data2             = \n| map_image          =\n| map_size           = \n| map_caption        = \n| title              = Mayor\n| before_election    = [[Kevin Faulconer]]\n| before_party       = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election     = TBD\n| after_party        = TBD\n}}\n\n{{Elections in California}}\nThe '''2020 San Diego mayoral election''' will be held to elect the [[Mayor of San Diego]]. Incumbent [[Kevin Faulconer]] was ineligible to run for a third term due to [[term limit]]s.\n\nThe officially non-partisan primary election was held on March 3, 2020. The top two finishers, California State Assemblymember [[Todd Gloria]] and San Diego City Council president pro tem [[Barbara Bry]] advanced to the general election. This guaranteed that a Democrat would be elected mayor of San Diego for only the third time since 1971.\n\nThe general election between Gloria and Bry will take place on November 3, 2020. \n\n==Candidates==\nNote: Municipal elections in California are officially nonpartisan. The parties below identify which party label each candidate would have run under if given the option.\n\n===Qualified===\n*Gita Applebaum Singh, media host<ref name=\"Filed\">{{cite news |last1=Garrick |first1=David |title=Forty candidates battling for seven open seats in San Diego next year |url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/communities/san-diego/story/2019-12-07/forty-candidates-battling-for-seven-open-seats-in-san-diego-next-year |work=The San Diego Union-Tribune |date=December 7, 2019}}</ref> (Party preference: [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]])\n*[[Barbara Bry]], [[San Diego City Council]]lor<ref name=derby>{{cite news |url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/columnists/michael-smolens/sd-me-smolens-mayoral-election-20180814-story.html |title=San Diego mayoral derby for 2020 has already started |newspaper=The San Diego Union-Tribune |date=August 17, 2018 |accessdate=December 6, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"dems_file\">{{cite news |last1=Horn |first1=Jonathan |title=Three key Democrats file to run for San Diego mayor in 2020 |url=https://www.10news.com/news/local-news/three-key-democrats-file-to-run-for-mayor |publisher=KGTV ABC10 News San Diego |date=January 3, 2019 |language=en |accessdate=January 7, 2019}}</ref> (Party preference: Democratic)\n*[[Todd Gloria]], [[California State Assembly]]member and former Acting [[Mayor of San Diego]]<ref name=derby/><ref name=dems_file/> (Party preference: Democratic)\n*Rich Riel, technology worker<ref name=\"Filed\" /> (Party preference: Hogwash)<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garrick |first1=David |title=Poll shows Gloria, Sherman continue to lead Bry in San Diego mayor\u2019s race |url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/communities/san-diego/story/2020-02-11/poll-shows-gloria-sherman-continue-to-lead-bry-in-san-diego-mayors-race |accessdate=February 18, 2020 |work=San Diego Union-Tribune |date=February 12, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Scott Sherman (politician)|Scott Sherman]], [[San Diego City Council]]lor<ref name=\"sherman\">{{cite news |last1=Clark |first1=Charles T. |last2=Garrick |first2=David |title=Republican City Councilman Scott Sherman files to run for mayor of San Diego |url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/politics/story/2019-11-29/republican-city-councillor-scott-sherman-files-papers-to-run-for-mayor-becoming-the-first-formidable |work=The San Diego Union-Tribune |date=November 29, 2019 |accessdate=November 29, 2019}}</ref> (Party preference:  [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]])\n*[[Tasha Williamson]], nonprofit executive<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hamblin |first1=Abby |last2=Gomez |first2=Luis |title=Who is Tasha Williamson? An in-depth 2020 San Diego mayor's race interview |url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/opinion/the-conversation/sd-who-is-tasha-williamson-san-diego-mayors-race-20190228-htmlstory.html |work=The San Diego Union-Tribune |date=February 28, 2019 |accessdate=April 28, 2019}}</ref> (Party preference: Democratic)\n\n===Declined===\n*[[Toni Atkins]], [[California State Senator]]<ref name=shaping>{{cite news |url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/politics/sd-me-smolens-mayor-20171219-story.html |title=Toni Atkins, Scott Peters are shaping the 2020 mayor's race \u2014 now |newspaper=The San Diego Union-Tribune |date=December 22, 2017 |accessdate=December 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Sklar |first1=Debbie L. |title=Todd Gloria Picks Up Endorsement from Toni Atkins in Mayoral Bid |url=https://timesofsandiego.com/politics/2019/03/21/todd-gloria-picks-up-endorsement-from-toni-atkins-in-mayoral-bid/ |work=Times of San Diego |date=March 22, 2019 |accessdate=March 31, 2019}}</ref> (Party preference: Democratic)\n*Cory Briggs, attorney<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garrick|first1=David|title=Briggs, vocal City Hall critic, will run for San Diego mayor in 2020|url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/politics/sd-me-briggs-mayor-20190123-story.html |work=The San Diego Union-Tribune |date=November 23, 2018 |accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Halverstadt |first1=Lisa |title=The Guys Who Want to Rep Downtown Don't Want a Downtown Convadium |url=https://www.voiceofsandiego.org/topics/politics/the-guys-who-want-to-rep-downtown-dont-want-a-downtown-convadium/ |work=Voice of San Diego |date=April 6, 2016 |accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Graham |first1=Marty |title=Briggs pulls out of San Diego mayor race |url=https://www.sandiegoreader.com/news/2019/may/15/ticker-briggs-pulls-out-san-diego-mayor-race/ |work=San Diego Reader |date=May 15, 2019 |language=en |accessdate=May 16, 2019}}</ref> (Party preference: [[Independent politician|None]])\n*[[Chris Cate]], San Diego City Councillor<ref name=derby/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Libby |first1=Sara |last2=Rivard |first2=Ry |title=Morning Report: Big Changes at City Hall |url=https://www.voiceofsandiego.org/topics/news/morning-report-meet-san-diegos-new-city-council/ |work=Voice of San Diego |date=November 7, 2018 |accessdate=January 17, 2019}}</ref> (Party preference: Republican)\n*[[John H. Cox|John Cox]], businessman and nominee for [[Governor of California]] in [[2018 California gubernatorial election|2018]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marinucci |first1=Carla |title=Former GOP gubernatorial candidate John Cox isn't ruling out another run for top job|url=https://www.politico.com/states/california/story/2019/02/22/former-gop-gubernatorial-candidate-john-cox-isnt-ruling-out-another-run-for-top-job-869142 |work=[[Politico]] |date=February 22, 2019 |accessdate=February 22, 2019}}</ref> (Party preference: Republican)\n*[[Carl DeMaio]], former member of [[San Diego City Council]], and [[2012 San Diego mayoral election|candidate for mayor in 2012]].<ref>https://ivn.us/2018/04/02/reform-ca-chair-carl-demaio-talks-gas-tax-san-diego-leadership-and-a-2020-mayoral-run/</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Clark |first1=Charles T. |last2=Cook |first2=Morgan |title=Carl DeMaio announces challenge for Rep. Duncan Hunter's congressional seat |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2019-08-05/carl-demaio-announces-challenge-for-rep-duncan-hunters-congressional-seat |work=Los Angeles Times |date=August 5, 2019 |accessdate=August 6, 2019}}</ref> (Party preference: Republican)\n*[[Mark Kersey]], San Diego City Councillor<ref name=derby/><ref name=\"Filed\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Jennewein |first1=Chris |title=Another San Diego Republican Leaves The Party Amid Political 'Polarization' |url=https://timesofsandiego.com/politics/2019/04/29/another-san-diego-republican-leaves-the-party-amid-political-polarization/ |work=Times of San Diego |date=April 29, 2019 |accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref> (Party preference: None)\n*[[Scott Peters (politician)|Scott Peters]], member of the [[United States House of Representatives]]<ref name=derby/><ref name=dems_file/><ref name=shaping/><ref name=Peters>{{cite news |last1=Service |first1=City News |title=Rep. Scott Peters To Run For Re-Election Instead Of Mayor In 2020 |url=https://www.kpbs.org/news/2019/jan/16/rep-scott-peters-run-re-election-instead-mayor-202/ |publisher=KPBS Public Media |date=January 16, 2019 |language=en |accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref> (Party preference: Democratic)\n*Shelley Zimmerman, former [[Chief of Police]] of the [[San Diego Police Department]]<ref name=derby/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kucher |first1=Karen |title=Former police chief Zimmerman won't run for mayor in 2020; takes post with National University |url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/public-safety/sd-me-zimmerman-police-chief-mayor-national-20190212-story.html |work=The San Diego Union-Tribune |date=February 12, 2019 |accessdate=February 12, 2019}}</ref> (Party preference: None)\n\n==Campaign==\nThe campaign for the mayor's office kicked off in early January 2019, when [[San Diego City Council]] president pro tem [[Barbara Bry]] and [[California State Assembly]]member [[Todd Gloria]] officially announced their candidacies.<ref name=Peters/> They were joined in the race later that month by [[Tasha Williamson]], a community activist who works with families who have lost members from police violence.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marx |first1=Jesse |title=Morning Report: The Story Behind a Rape Accusation at an Escondido Middle School |url=https://www.voiceofsandiego.org/topics/news/morning-report-the-story-behind-a-rape-accusation-at-an-escondido-middle-school/ |work=Voice of San Diego |date=January 22, 2019 |accessdate=July 15, 2019}}</ref> In November 2019, with less than 100 days to go before the primary, city council member [[Scott Sherman (politician)|Scott Sherman]] became the first major Republican to file papers for the mayoral race.<ref name=\"sherman\" />\n\nOne of the issues distinguishing the candidates from each other was housing policy. Local activist attorney Cory Briggs announced in January 2019 that he would run for mayor based on opposition to the loosening of development restrictions proposed by incumbent mayor [[Kevin Faulconer]] in his State of the City speech. However, Briggs dropped out of the race by May 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jennewein |first1=Chris |title=Activist Lawyer Cory Briggs Pulls Out of San Diego Mayoral Race |url=https://timesofsandiego.com/politics/2019/05/15/activist-lawyer-cory-briggs-pulls-out-of-san-diego-mayoral-race/ |work=Times of San Diego |date=May 16, 2019 |accessdate=July 15, 2019}}</ref> In a June 2019 campaign email, Bry came out in favor of strong local control over land use and against statewide legislation to preempt local governments' ability to restrict new development. Gloria favored statewide efforts to increase housing supply, aligning himself with the pro-housing development \"Yes In My Back Yard\" ([[YIMBY]]) movement.<ref name=\"Homes\">{{cite news |last1=Lewis |first1=Scott |title='They're Coming for Our Homes': Bry Blasts YIMBY Movement |url=https://www.voiceofsandiego.org/topics/politics/theyre-coming-for-our-homes-bry-blasts-yimby-movement/ |work=Voice of San Diego |date=June 26, 2019 |accessdate=July 15, 2019}}</ref> Sherman emphasized market-based solutions to housing upon his entry into the race in late 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lewis |first1=Scott |last2=Keatts |first2=Andrew |title=Politics Report: Hello, New Mayor's Race |url=https://www.voiceofsandiego.org/topics/politics/politics-report-hello-new-mayors-race/ |work=Voice of San Diego |date=December 7, 2019 |accessdate=December 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Gloria was accused of collecting funds for his 2020 re-election campaign to the State Assembly before filing his intent to run with the state in violation of state law.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garcia |first1=Alberto |title=Todd Gloria Failed to File Candidacy Form Before Raising Money |url=http://laprensa-sandiego.org/featured/todd-gloria-failed-to-file-candidacy-form-before-raising-money/ |work=La Prensa San Diego |date=August 12, 2019 |accessdate=August 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stone |first1=Ken |title=Todd Gloria Files for Assembly Re-Election While Running for San Diego Mayor |url=https://timesofsandiego.com/politics/2019/08/13/todd-gloria-files-for-assembly-re-election-while-running-for-san-diego-mayor/l |work=Times of San Diego |date=August 13, 2019 |accessdate=August 20, 2019}}</ref> Gloria claimed this was a technical oversight and filed the relevant paperwork the next day.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hargrove |first1=Dorian |title=Mayoral Candidate Todd Gloria Accused of Laundering Political Funds |url=https://www.nbcsandiego.com/news/local/Mayoral-Candidate-Todd-Gloria-Accused-of-Laundering-Political-Funds-545390301.html |publisher=NBC San Diego |date=August 15, 2019 |accessdate=August 20, 2019}}</ref> In November 2019, Gloria settled the case with the [[California Fair Political Practices Commission]], paying a $200 fine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stone |first1=Ken |title=Assemblyman Todd Gloria Pays Fine for Violating Political Reform Act Rules |url=https://timesofsandiego.com/politics/2019/11/08/assemblyman-todd-gloria-pays-fine-for-violating-political-reform-act-rules/ |work=Times of San Diego |date=November 9, 2019 |accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Endorsements==\n{{Endorsements box\n| title = Barbara Bry\n| list =\n;Officeholders\n*[[Mike Levin]], [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[California's 49th congressional district]]<ref name=\"Mapp_4-9-19\" />\n*Dianne Jacob, member of the [[San Diego County Board of Supervisors]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jennewein |first1=Chris |title=GOP's Dianne Jacob, County Supervisor, Endorses Barbara Bry for Mayor |url=https://timesofsandiego.com/politics/2020/02/03/gops-dianne-jacob-county-supervisor-endorses-barbara-bry-for-mayor/ |accessdate=February 7, 2020 |work=Times of San Diego |date=February 4, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Donna Frye]], former member of the [[San Diego City Council]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Keatts |first1=Andrew |last2=Lewis |first2=Scott |title=Politics Report: Populist Bry Campaign Scores Populist Endorsement |url=https://www.voiceofsandiego.org/topics/politics/politics-report-populist-bry-campaign-scores-populist-endorsement/ |work=Voice of San Diego |date=December 14, 2019 |accessdate=December 14, 2019}}</ref>\n;Other individuals\n*Sunday Gover, 2018 candidate for [[California's 77th State Assembly district]]<ref name=\"Brown\" />\n*[[Genevi\u00e9ve Jones-Wright]], 2018 candidate for [[San Diego County District Attorney]]<ref name=\"Brown\" />\n}}\n{{Endorsements box\n| title = Todd Gloria\n| list =\n;Officeholders\n*[[Gavin Newsom]], [[Governor of California]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jennewein |first1=Chris |title=Todd Gloria Gets Gov. Newsom's Endorsement in San Diego Mayor's Race |url=https://timesofsandiego.com/politics/2019/08/08/todd-gloria-gets-gov-newsoms-endorsement-in-san-diego-mayors-race/ |work=Times of San Diego |date=August 9, 2019 |accessdate=August 9, 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Jerry Brown]], 34th and 39th [[Governor of California]]<ref name=Brown>{{cite news |last1=Jennewein |first1=Chris |title=Former Gov. Jerry Brown Endorses Todd Gloria for San Diego Mayor |url=https://timesofsandiego.com/politics/2019/06/21/former-gov-jerry-brown-endorses-todd-gloria-for-san-diego-mayor/ |date=June 21, 2019 |accessdate=June 21, 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Dianne Feinstein]], [[United States Senate|United States Senator]] for California<ref>{{cite tweet |user=toddgloria |number=1192523570326278144 |date=November 7, 2019 |title=Big news! Senator @DianneFeinstein has endorsed our campaign... |accessdate=November 7, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"steeper\">{{cite news |last1=Smolens |first1=Michael |title=Column: Barbara Bry's climb to the mayor's office just got steeper |url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/columnists/story/2019-12-08/column-barbara-brys-mayoral-bid-just-got-tougher-but-remember-no-one-has-voted-yet |work=The San Diego Union-Tribune |date=December 8, 2019 |accessdate=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Kamala Harris]], [[United States Senate|United States Senator]] for California<ref>{{cite tweet |user=ToddGloria |number=1197228785969459200 |date=November 20, 2019 |title=So proud to announce @KamalaHarris has... |accessdate=November 23, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"steeper\" />\n*[[Susan Davis (politician)|Susan Davis]], [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[California's 53rd congressional district]]<ref name=\"Mapp_4-9-19\">{{cite news |last1=Mapp |first1=Lauren J. |title=Local Labor Union Endorses Todd Gloria in 2020 Mayoral Election |url=https://timesofsandiego.com/politics/2019/04/08/local-labor-union-endorses-todd-gloria-in-2020-mayoral-election/ |work=Times of San Diego |date=April 9, 2019 |accessdate=April 27, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Gloria_endorse\">{{cite web |title=Endorsements |url=http://toddgloria.com/