{"title_page": "Danka system", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}}\n[[File:\u5b97\u9580\u4eba\u5225\u6539\u5e33 Shumon Jinbetsu Aratamecho.jpg|thumb|275 px|The ''sh\u016bmon ninbetsu aratamech\u014d'', or danka register, of a village called Kumagawa near [[Fussa, Tokyo]]]]\nThe {{nihongo|'''danka system'''|\u6a80\u5bb6\u5236\u5ea6|''danka seido''}}, also known as {{nihongo|'''jidan system'''|\u5bfa\u6a80\u5236\u5ea6|''jidan seido''}} is a system of voluntary and long-term affiliation between [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] temples and households in use in Japan since the [[Heian period]].<ref name=\"marcure\"/> In it, households (the ''danka'') financially support a [[Buddhist temple]] which, in exchange, provides for their spiritual needs.<ref name=\"marcure\">Marcure (1985)</ref> Although its existence long predates the [[Edo period]] (1603\u20131868), the system is best known for its repressive use made at that time by the [[Tokugawa shogunate|Tokugawa]], who made the affiliation with a Buddhist temple [[Freedom of religion|compulsory]] to all citizens. \n\nDuring the Tokugawa shogunate, the system was turned into a citizen registration network; supposedly intended to stop the diffusion of Christianity and help detect [[Hidden Christians of Japan|hidden Christians]], it soon became a government-mandated and Buddhist temple-run system to monitor and control the population as a whole.<ref name=\"tamamuro\">Tamamuro Fumio</ref> For this reason, it survived intact long after Christianity in Japan had been eradicated. The system as it existed in Tokugawa times is sometimes called {{nihongo|''terauke'' system |\u5bfa\u8acb\u5236\u5ea6|terauke seido}} because of the certification (or ''terauke'', because the ''tera'', or temple would issue an ''uke'', or certificate) issued by a Buddhist temple that a citizen was not a Christian.<ref name=\"hur\">Nam-lin Hur</ref> \n\nThe mandatory ''danka'' system was officially abolished during the Meiji period, but continues nonetheless to exists as a voluntary association between the two sides, constitutes a major part of the income of most temples and defines as before the relationship between households and temples.<ref name=\"marcure\"/>\n\n== The ''terauke''==\nThe ''danka'' system changed drastically in 1638 when, in reaction to the [[Shimabara Rebellion]] (1637\u201338), the [[bakufu]] decided to stamp out the Christian religion using it as a tool.<ref name=\"hur\"/> The relationship between temple and ''danka'', until then voluntary, was formalized and made compulsory: Buddhist temples were ordered to start writing ''terauke'' certificates for all their {{nihongo|''danka''|\u6a80\u5bb6}}, while households on their part had the duty to become ''danka'' of the closest Buddhist temple, regardless of its sect (Nichiren, J\u014ddo, Rinzai, etc.), and to obtain from it a ''terauke''.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> Although never written into law,<ref name=\"hur\"/> this use of the system nonetheless quickly became a universal and extremely important feature of Tokugawa Japan.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> Administratively speaking, all Japanese, Shinto priests included, became an integral part of the Buddhist bureaucratic organization, which in turn referred to the Tokugawa.\n\nThe system had three tiers, with at the lowest the temple which issued the ''terauke''. Local government officials would then collect all ''terauke'', bind them in ledgers called {{nihongo|''sh\u016bmon ninbetsu aratamech\u014d'' |\u5b97\u9580\u4eba\u5225\u6539\u5e33}}<ref name=\"hur\"/> and submit them to higher authorities.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> The purpose was to force Christians to become affiliated to a Buddhist temple, while making the monitoring of suspected Christians easier.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/>\n\nThe very first registries in existence are dated between 1638 and 1640 and, unsurprisingly, are found in areas where the Christian religion was strong, for example [[Kyoto]], its province and [[Ky\u016bsh\u016b]].<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> Registries in other areas aren't found until the second half of the 17th century, but individual ''terauke'', which clearly served the same purpose, are.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/>\n\nBecause in 1664 the bakufu ordered to all [[daimy\u014d]]s the establishment in their domain of an officer of religious investigation called {{nihongo|magistrate of religion|\u5b97\u9580\u5949\u884c|sh\u016bmon bugy\u014d}} or {{nihongo|magistrate of temples and shrines|\u5bfa\u793e\u5949\u884c|jisha bugy\u014d}}, from the following year registries of religious affiliation started being produced nationwide.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> \n\nIn 1671 the registry's format was standardized. The document had to record all peasant households, state the number of men and women of each town, plus the totals for all districts and the province.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> The intendant had to keep the registry and send a one-page summary to higher authorities.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> Further, all departures from the community due to marriage, work or death were to be recorded. This registry format was maintained unchanged until 1870, three years into the [[Meiji era]].<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> Since the order explicitly states that \"''Naturally, it is appropriate to investigate many things, and not only at the time of inquiry into religion''\",<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> the system clearly had from the beginning purposes that went beyond religion. The result was an [[Edo]] equivalent of today's household registry, set apart only by the temple's obligation to specify a family temple and the citizens' to obtain a ''terauke''.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> In some regions, the right to issue certificates was called {{nihongo|''sh\u016bhanken''|\u5b97\u5224\u6a29}}\uff0ca right which gradually became a source of great power for the temples.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> Not only was a certificate issued after payment of a fee, but it gave religious authorities the power of life and death over parishioners.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/>\n\nThis document had to be obtained every year after an inspection at one's temple of affiliation.<ref name=\"hur\"/> Those who for some reason couldn't obtain a temple certification were recorded as [[hinin]] (''non-persons'') and thereafter subject to discrimination,<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> or simply executed as Christians.<ref name=\"hur\"/> Not only peasants, but even samurai and Shint\u014d priests could not live or function within society without a ''terauke'',<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> which had assumed a role similar to that of identity papers now. It was necessary to marry, to travel, to gain access to certain jobs.<ref name=\"Sheid\"/> After 1729 the breaking of ties between a temple and a ''danka'' (or {{nihongo|''ridan''|\u96e2\u58c7}}) was formally outlawed, making the link between a ''danka'' and a temple impossible to break.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> This eliminated competition for parishioners between temples, giving a man and his family no possibility to change temple of affiliation. By the late 17th century the system had become an integral part of the Tokugawa state apparatus.<ref name=\"hur\"/> It also contributed to the enforcement of [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] orthodoxy; the ''danka'' system was used to stamp out ''[[Ikk\u014d-sh\u016b]]'' and other schools of Buddhism deemed \"deviant\" in the Tokugawa era.<ref>{{cite book|last=Josephson |first=Jason |title=The Invention of Religion in Japan|publisher=University of Chicago Press|page=39|location = Chicago|year=2012|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gxzuzIszO60C}}</ref>\n\n== The appearance of the ''Goj\u014dmoku'' ==\nThe life of the ''dankas'' were later made even more difficult by a document that greatly expanded a temple's powers over those affiliated to it. Purporting to be a ''bakufu'' law regulating in great detail the certification of religious affiliation process, it appeared around 1735 and had thereafter large circulation all over Japan.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> Dated 1613 and called \"Individual Rules Concerning the Certification of Religious Affiliation for Danka\"(''Goj\u014dmoku Sh\u016bmon Danna Ukeai No Okite'' (\u5fa1\u6761\u76ee\u5b97\u9580\u65e6\u90a3\u8acb\u5408\u4e4b\u639f), usually abbreviated in just ''Goj\u014dmoku''), it is demonstrably a forgery, probably created by the temples themselves, whose interests it serves.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> \n\nThat the document is a fake is proven beyond doubt by the fact that it lists among the forbidden religions not only Christianity, but also the {{nihongo|[[Fuju-fuse]]|\u4e0d\u53d7\u4e0d\u65bd}} and {{nihongo|Hiden|\u60b2\u7530}} subschools of the [[Nichiren]] [[sect]]. Since the two schools were outlawed respectively in 1669 and 1691, the date of issue must have been deliberately misstated.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> The likely reason this particular date was chosen is that it is the year in which Tokugawa Ieyasu's {{nihongo|\"Order to Expel Christian Priests\"|\u4f34\u5929\u9023\u8ffd\u653e\u4ee4|Bateren Tsuih\u014drei}} was issued, and because the following year temples were ordered to start issuing ''terauke''.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/>\n\nThe document is often found in temples and collections all over the country and it appears to have been believed genuine even by most [[Meiji period]] historians.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> The Goj\u014dmoku, which gives temples additional power over parishioners, is mentioned occasionally by temple registries and, when a ''danka'' did not meet its conditions, the temple certification wasn't issued.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> Its provisions caused considerable problems between ''danka'' and temples.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/>\n\nThe document first defined four duties of the ''danka''. \n* Duty to visit the temple on several yearly occasion. Failure to make the visits could cause the removal of the ''danka'''s name from the registry.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> \n* Duty to perform two services on the day of the ancestor memorial service. Failure to provide adequate entertainment for the priest meant being branded as a Christian.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> \n* Duty to make the family temple perform all memorial and funerary services.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> \n* Duty of anyone capable of walking to be present at memorial services for ancestors.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/>   \n\nIt then gave five rights to its temple.\n\n* A ''danka'' had to perform certain acts in favor of the temple, including making offerings and providing free labor. Failure to do so meant being branded as a Fuju-fuse sect member.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/>\n* A ''danka'' had to obey its temple and give money to its priests.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/>  \n* Regardless of how long a ''danka'' group had been faithful, it was always to be subject to religious investigation to determine the possible emergence of heresy.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> \n* After someone's death, just looking at the corpse the priest could determine what the defunct's true religion had been.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> \n* The ''danka'' was always to follow his temple's orders.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/>\n\n== Consequences of the ''danka'' system==\nThe consequences of two centuries and a half of ''terauke'' use and of the bureaucratization of Buddhism were numerous and profound, first of all for Buddhism itself.\n\n=== Structural distortions ===\nThe chasm between allowed and forbidden sects became much deeper than it had been.<ref name=\"Sheid\"/> If on the one hand Buddhism allowed a diversification of its authorized sects, on the other it punished tendencies that put into question the political status quo.<ref name=\"Sheid\"/> A ''danka'' was registered at the closest temple regardless of its religious affiliations, so these became gradually less important.<ref name=\"Sheid\"/> As a consequence of all these factors, differences among sects allowed by the government got watered down and Buddhism became more uniform, not least because the Shogunate had a say in matters of religious orthodoxy.<ref name=\"Sheid\"/> \n\nDuring the Edo period, Buddhism therefore offered few new ideas (with the possible exception of the reform of [[Zen]] sects).<ref name=\"Sheid\"/> On the contrary, the development during the same period of Japanese Confucianism and Shinto, and the birth of the so-called \"New Religions\" produced interesting ideas.<ref name=\"Sheid\"/>\n\n=== The advent of \"funerary Buddhism\" ===\nEven though the original intent of Buddhism was the spreading of the teachings of Buddha, Buddhist temples in Japan today are primarily cemeteries.<ref name=\"heine\"/><ref name=\"Tamura214\">Tamura (2000:214)</ref> The so-called {{nihongo|''s\u014dshiki bukky\u014d''|\u846c\u5f0f\u4ecf\u6559}} or ''Funerary Buddhism'' of today, lampooned for example in [[Juzo Itami]]'s film [[The Funeral (1984 movie)|The Funeral]], where Japanese Buddhism's essential function has become confined to the performance of funerals and memorial services, is a direct consequence of the ''danka'' system, as is the sale of posthumous names (or {{nihongo|''[[kaimy\u014d]]''|\u6212\u540d}}).<ref name=\"Sheid\"/> As far as Buddhism was concerned, the defining feature of the ''danka'' system during the Edo period was the fact that it guaranteed a steady stream of profits thanks to the mandatory funerary rites.<ref name=\"heine\">Heine</ref> This cash flow is what paid for the majority of the temples in Japan and guaranteed their proliferation, and is inseparable from the ''danka'' system.<ref name=\"heine\"/> Hence the tight association between Buddhism and death that continues to this day. When the formal dissolution of the whole ''danka'' system arrived after World War II, it meant for Buddhism a great loss of income, and therefore financial insecurity.<ref name=\"Tamura214\"/>\n\n=== The ''Haibutsu kishaku'' movement ===\nThe use of ''terauke'' and the widespread resentment it created are considered to be one of the primary causes of the ''[[haibutsu kishaku]]'', a violent and spontaneous movement that at the beginning of the [[Meiji era]] caused the destruction of a high number of temples all over Japan. The government's official policy of separation of Shinto and Buddhism (''[[Shinbutsu bunri]]'') of the time, while not directly responsible for this destruction, provided the trigger that released pent-up energy. Considering Buddhism's close association with the Tokugawa, it can't be a surprise that Buddhist monks were regarded as state agents and that several sectors of the Edo society began trying to find alternate ways to satisfy their spiritual needs.<ref name=\"Sheid\">Bernhard Scheid</ref> \n\nIn spite of its history, Buddhism had however decisive advantages over both [[Shinto]] and [[Confucianism]] that during the Meiji era made it impossible to replace it with either.<ref name=\"leiden\">Paul B. Watt</ref> With its many rituals (the ''j\u016bsan butsuji'', or thirteen Buddhist rituals), Buddhism could better help people cope with death.<ref name=\"leiden\"/> Moreover, Shinto associates death and pollution, so it is intrinsically less suitable to funerary ceremonies, while Confucianism in Japan did not concern itself much with funerals.<ref name=\"leiden\"/> Lastly, Buddhism had a country-wide infrastructure that neither Shinto nor Confucianism could match.<ref name=\"leiden\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Religion in Japan]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== References ==\n* {{cite journal\n  |last=Marcure\n  |first=Kenneth\n  |date=Spring 1985\n  |title=The Danka System\n  |journal=Monumenta Nipponica\n  |publisher=Sophia University\n  |location=Tokyo\n  |volume=40\n  |issue=1\n  |pages=39\u201367\n  |doi=10.2307/2385001\n  |jstor=2385001\n}}\n* Nam-Lin Hur, Death and social order in Tokugawa Japan: Buddhism, anti-Christianity, and the danka system, Harvard University Asia Center, 2007; pp. 1-30 (The Rise of Funerary Buddhism in Tokugawa Japan). [https://web.archive.org/web/20120331070517/http://www.fas.harvard.edu/~asiactr/publications/pdfs/Hur%20intro.pdf Internet archive]\n* [[Bernhard Scheid]], [https://web.archive.org/web/20150705145949/http://www.univie.ac.at/rel_jap/an/Geschichte/Terauke Inquisition unter buddhistischen Vorzeichen] {{in lang|de}} retrieved on March 20, 2008\n* Paul B. Watt, [https://web.archive.org/web/20120302110710/http://www.let.leidenuniv.nl/history/itinerario/bookreviews-16.html Review of \"Nam-Lin Hur, Death and Social Order in Tokugawa Japan: Buddhism, Anti-Christianity, and the Danka System\"] retrieved on March 20, 2008\n*{{cite book\n |last=Tamura\n |first=Yoshiro\n |title=Japanese Buddhism \u2013 A Cultural History\n |publisher=Kosei Publishing Company\n |location=Tokyo\n |year=2000 \n |edition=First\n |pages=232 pages\n |chapter=The Birth of the Japanese nation\n |isbn=4-333-01684-3\n }}\n* [http://law.hamline.edu/files/HeineRev.pdf Review of \"Death and Social Order in Tokugawa Japan: Buddhism, anti-Christianity and the Danka System\" by Nam-Lin Hur] By Steven Heine, retrieved on October 20, 2008\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* Tamamuro Fumio (2001), [https://web.archive.org/web/20110722073943/http://nirc.nanzan-u.ac.jp/publications/jjrs/pdf/611.pdf \"Local Society and the Temple-Parishioner Relationship within the Bakufu\u2019s Governance Structure\"], Japanese Journal of Religious Studies 28/3-4, 261\u201329\n* Tamamuro Fumio (2009), [https://web.archive.org/web/20151019211505/http://nirc.nanzan-u.ac.jp/nfile/2977 The Development of the Temple-Parishioner System], Japanese Journal of Religious Studies 36/1, 11\u201326\n\n[[Category:Japanese Buddhist terminology]]\n[[Category:Buddhism in Japan]]\n[[Category:Religious policy in Japan]]\n[[Category:Buddhism in the Edo period]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}}\n[[File:\u5b97\u9580\u4eba\u5225\u6539\u5e33 Shumon Jinbetsu Aratamecho.jpg|thumb|275 px|The ''sh\u016bmon ninbetsu aratamech\u014d'', or danka register, of a village called Kumagawa near [[Fussa, Tokyo]]]]\nThe {{nihongo|'''danka system'''|\u6a80\u5bb6\u5236\u5ea6|''danka seido''}}, also known as {{nihongo|'''jidan system'''|\u5bfa\u6a80\u5236\u5ea6|''jidan seido''}} is a system of voluntary and long-term affiliation between [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] temples and households in use in Japan since the [[Heian period]].<ref name=\"marcure\"/> In it, households (the ''danka'') financially support a [[Buddhist temple]] which, in exchange, provides for their spiritual needs.<ref name=\"marcure\">Marcure (1985)</ref> Although its existence long predates the [[Edo period]] (1603\u20131868), the system is best known for its repressive use made at that time by the [[Tokugawa shogunate|Tokugawa]], who made the affiliation with a Buddhist temple [[Freedom of religion|compulsory]] to all citizens. \n\nDuring the Tokugawa shogunate, the system was turned into a citizen registration network; supposedly intended to stop the diffusion of Christianity and help detect [[Hidden Christians of Japan|hidden Christians]], it soon became a government-mandated and Buddhist temple-run system to monitor and control the population as a whole.<ref name=\"tamamuro\">Tamamuro Fumio</ref> For this reason, it survived intact long after Christianity in Japan had been eradicated. The system as it existed in Tokugawa times is sometimes called {{nihongo|''terauke'' system |\u5bfa\u8acb\u5236\u5ea6|terauke seido}} because of the certification (or ''terauke'', because the ''tera'', or temple would issue an ''uke'', or certificate) issued by a Buddhist temple that a citizen was not a Christian.<ref name=\"hur\">Nam-lin Hur</ref> \n\nThe mandatory ''danka'' system was officially abolished during the Meiji period, but continues nonetheless to exists as a voluntary association between the two sides, constitutes a major part of the income of most temples and defines as before the relationship between households and temples.<ref name=\"marcure\"/>\n\n== The ''terauke''==\nThe ''danka'' system changed drastically in 1638 when, in reaction to the [[Shimabara Rebellion]] (1637\u201338), the [[bakufu]] decided to stamp out the Christian religion using it as a tool.<ref name=\"hur\"/> The relationship between temple and ''danka'', until then voluntary, was formalized and made compulsory: Buddhist temples were ordered to start writing ''terauke'' certificates for all their {{nihongo|''danka''|\u6a80\u5bb6}}, while households on their part had the duty to become ''danka'' of the closest Buddhist temple, regardless of its sect (Nichiren, J\u014ddo, Rinzai, etc.), and to obtain from it a ''terauke''.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> Although never written into law,<ref name=\"hur\"/> this use of the system nonetheless quickly became a universal and extremely important feature of Tokugawa Japan.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> Administratively speaking, all Japanese, Shinto priests included, became an integral part of the Buddhist bureaucratic organization, which in turn referred to the Tokugawa.\n\nThe system had three tiers, with at the lowest the temple which issued the ''terauke''. Local government officials would then collect all ''terauke'', bind them in ledgers called {{nihongo|''sh\u016bmon ninbetsu aratamech\u014d'' |\u5b97\u9580\u4eba\u5225\u6539\u5e33}}<ref name=\"hur\"/> and submit them to higher authorities.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> The purpose was to force Christians to become affiliated to a Buddhist temple, while making the monitoring of suspected Christians easier.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/>\n\nThe very first registries in existence are dated between 1638 and 1640 and, unsurprisingly, are found in areas where the Christian religion was strong, for example [[Kyoto]], its province and [[Ky\u016bsh\u016b]].<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> Registries in other areas aren't found until the second half of the 17th century, but individual ''terauke'', which clearly served the same purpose, are.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/>\n\nBecause in 1664 the bakufu ordered to all [[daimy\u014d]]s the establishment in their domain of an officer of religious investigation called {{nihongo|magistrate of religion|\u5b97\u9580\u5949\u884c|sh\u016bmon bugy\u014d}} or {{nihongo|magistrate of temples and shrines|\u5bfa\u793e\u5949\u884c|jisha bugy\u014d}}, from the following year registries of religious affiliation started being produced nationwide.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> \n\nIn 1671 the registry's format was standardized. The document had to record all peasant households, state the number of men and women of each town, plus the totals for all districts and the province.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> The intendant had to keep the registry and send a one-page summary to higher authorities.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> Further, all departures from the community due to marriage, work or death were to be recorded. This registry format was maintained unchanged until 1870, three years into the [[Meiji era]].<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> Since the order explicitly states that \"''Naturally, it is appropriate to investigate many things, and not only at the time of inquiry into religion''\",<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> the system clearly had from the beginning purposes that went beyond religion. The result was an [[Edo]] equivalent of today's household registry, set apart only by the temple's obligation to specify a family temple and the citizens' to obtain a ''terauke''.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> In some regions, the right to issue certificates was called {{nihongo|''sh\u016bhanken''|\u5b97\u5224\u6a29}}\uff0ca right which gradually became a source of great power for the temples.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> Not only was a certificate issued after payment of a fee, but it gave religious authorities the power of life and death over parishioners.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/>\n\nThis document had to be obtained every year after an inspection at one's temple of affiliation.<ref name=\"hur\"/> Those who for some reason couldn't obtain a temple certification were recorded as [[hinin]] (''non-persons'') and thereafter subject to discrimination,<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> or simply executed as Christians.<ref name=\"hur\"/> Not only peasants, but even samurai and Shint\u014d priests could not live or function within society without a ''terauke'',<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> which had assumed a role similar to that of identity papers now. It was necessary to get married, to travel, to gain access to certain jobs.<ref name=\"Sheid\"/> After 1729 the breaking of ties between a temple and a ''danka'' (or {{nihongo|''ridan''|\u96e2\u58c7}}) was formally outlawed, making the link between a ''danka'' and a temple impossible to break.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> This eliminated competition for parishioners between temples, giving a man and his family no possibility to change temple of affiliation. By the late 17th century the system had become an integral part of the Tokugawa state apparatus.<ref name=\"hur\"/> It also contributed to the enforcement of [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] orthodoxy; the ''danka'' system was used to stamp out ''[[Ikk\u014d-sh\u016b]]'' and other schools of Buddhism deemed \"deviant\" in the Tokugawa era.<ref>{{cite book|last=Josephson |first=Jason |title=The Invention of Religion in Japan|publisher=University of Chicago Press|page=39|location = Chicago|year=2012|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gxzuzIszO60C}}</ref>\n\n== The appearance of the ''Goj\u014dmoku'' ==\nThe life of the ''dankas'' were later made even more difficult by a document that greatly expanded a temple's powers over those affiliated to it. Purporting to be a ''bakufu'' law regulating in great detail the certification of religious affiliation process, it appeared around 1735 and had thereafter large circulation all over Japan.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> Dated 1613 and called \"Individual Rules Concerning the Certification of Religious Affiliation for Danka\"(''Goj\u014dmoku Sh\u016bmon Danna Ukeai No Okite'' (\u5fa1\u6761\u76ee\u5b97\u9580\u65e6\u90a3\u8acb\u5408\u4e4b\u639f), usually abbreviated in just ''Goj\u014dmoku''), it is demonstrably a forgery, probably created by the temples themselves, whose interests it serves.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> \n\nThat the document is a fake is proven beyond doubt by the fact that it lists among the forbidden religions not only Christianity, but also the {{nihongo|[[Fuju-fuse]]|\u4e0d\u53d7\u4e0d\u65bd}} and {{nihongo|Hiden|\u60b2\u7530}} subschools of the [[Nichiren]] [[sect]]. Since the two schools were outlawed respectively in 1669 and 1691, the date of issue must have been deliberately misstated.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> The likely reason this particular date was chosen is that it is the year in which Tokugawa Ieyasu's {{nihongo|\"Order to Expel Christian Priests\"|\u4f34\u5929\u9023\u8ffd\u653e\u4ee4|Bateren Tsuih\u014drei}} was issued, and because the following year temples were ordered to start issuing ''terauke''.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/>\n\nThe document is often found in temples and collections all over the country and it appears to have been believed genuine even by most [[Meiji period]] historians.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> The Goj\u014dmoku, which gives temples additional power over parishioners, is mentioned occasionally by temple registries and, when a ''danka'' did not meet its conditions, the temple certification wasn't issued.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> Its provisions caused considerable problems between ''danka'' and temples.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/>\n\nThe document first defined four duties of the ''danka''. \n* Duty to visit the temple on several yearly occasion. Failure to make the visits could cause the removal of the ''danka'''s name from the registry.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> \n* Duty to perform two services on the day of the ancestor memorial service. Failure to provide adequate entertainment for the priest meant being branded as a Christian.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> \n* Duty to make the family temple perform all memorial and funerary services.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> \n* Duty of anyone capable of walking to be present at memorial services for ancestors.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/>   \n\nIt then gave five rights to its temple.\n\n* A ''danka'' had to perform certain acts in favor of the temple, including making offerings and providing free labor. Failure to do so meant being branded as a Fuju-fuse sect member.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/>\n* A ''danka'' had to obey its temple and give money to its priests.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/>  \n* Regardless of how long a ''danka'' group had been faithful, it was always to be subject to religious investigation to determine the possible emergence of heresy.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> \n* After someone's death, just looking at the corpse the priest could determine what the defunct's true religion had been.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/> \n* The ''danka'' was always to follow his temple's orders.<ref name=\"tamamuro\"/>\n\n== Consequences of the ''danka'' system==\nThe consequences of two centuries and a half of ''terauke'' use and of the bureaucratization of Buddhism were numerous and profound, first of all for Buddhism itself.\n\n=== Structural distortions ===\nThe chasm between allowed and forbidden sects became much deeper than it had been.<ref name=\"Sheid\"/> If on the one hand Buddhism allowed a diversification of its authorized sects, on the other it punished tendencies that put into question the political status quo.<ref name=\"Sheid\"/> A ''danka'' was registered at the closest temple regardless of its religious affiliations, so these became gradually less important.<ref name=\"Sheid\"/> As a consequence of all these factors, differences among sects allowed by the government got watered down and Buddhism became more uniform, not least because the Shogunate had a say in matters of religious orthodoxy.<ref name=\"Sheid\"/> \n\nDuring the Edo period, Buddhism therefore offered few new ideas (with the possible exception of the reform of [[Zen]] sects).<ref name=\"Sheid\"/> On the contrary, the development during the same period of Japanese Confucianism and Shinto, and the birth of the so-called \"New Religions\" produced interesting ideas.<ref name=\"Sheid\"/>\n\n=== The advent of \"funerary Buddhism\" ===\nEven though the original intent of Buddhism was the spreading of the teachings of Buddha, Buddhist temples in Japan today are primarily cemeteries.<ref name=\"heine\"/><ref name=\"Tamura214\">Tamura (2000:214)</ref> The so-called {{nihongo|''s\u014dshiki bukky\u014d''|\u846c\u5f0f\u4ecf\u6559}} or ''Funerary Buddhism'' of today, lampooned for example in [[Juzo Itami]]'s film [[The Funeral (1984 movie)|The Funeral]], where Japanese Buddhism's essential function has become confined to the performance of funerals and memorial services, is a direct consequence of the ''danka'' system, as is the sale of posthumous names (or {{nihongo|''[[kaimy\u014d]]''|\u6212\u540d}}).<ref name=\"Sheid\"/> As far as Buddhism was concerned, the defining feature of the ''danka'' system during the Edo period was the fact that it guaranteed a steady stream of profits thanks to the mandatory funerary rites.<ref name=\"heine\">Heine</ref> This cash flow is what paid for the majority of the temples in Japan and guaranteed their proliferation, and is inseparable from the ''danka'' system.<ref name=\"heine\"/> Hence the tight association between Buddhism and death that continues to this day. When the formal dissolution of the whole ''danka'' system arrived after World War II, it meant for Buddhism a great loss of income, and therefore financial insecurity.<ref name=\"Tamura214\"/>\n\n=== The ''Haibutsu kishaku'' movement ===\nThe use of ''terauke'' and the widespread resentment it created are considered to be one of the primary causes of the ''[[haibutsu kishaku]]'', a violent and spontaneous movement that at the beginning of the [[Meiji era]] caused the destruction of a high number of temples all over Japan. The government's official policy of separation of Shinto and Buddhism (''[[Shinbutsu bunri]]'') of the time, while not directly responsible for this destruction, provided the trigger that released pent-up energy. Considering Buddhism's close association with the Tokugawa, it can't be a surprise that Buddhist monks were regarded as state agents and that several sectors of the Edo society began trying to find alternate ways to satisfy their spiritual needs.<ref name=\"Sheid\">Bernhard Scheid</ref> \n\nIn spite of its history, Buddhism had however decisive advantages over both [[Shinto]] and [[Confucianism]] that during the Meiji era made it impossible to replace it with either.<ref name=\"leiden\">Paul B. Watt</ref> With its many rituals (the ''j\u016bsan butsuji'', or thirteen Buddhist rituals), Buddhism could better help people cope with death.<ref name=\"leiden\"/> Moreover, Shinto associates death and pollution, so it is intrinsically less suitable to funerary ceremonies, while Confucianism in Japan did not concern itself much with funerals.<ref name=\"leiden\"/> Lastly, Buddhism had a country-wide infrastructure that neither Shinto nor Confucianism could match.<ref name=\"leiden\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Religion in Japan]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== References ==\n* {{cite journal\n  |last=Marcure\n  |first=Kenneth\n  |date=Spring 1985\n  |title=The Danka System\n  |journal=Monumenta Nipponica\n  |publisher=Sophia University\n  |location=Tokyo\n  |volume=40\n  |issue=1\n  |pages=39\u201367\n  |doi=10.2307/2385001\n  |jstor=2385001\n}}\n* Nam-Lin Hur, Death and social order in Tokugawa Japan: Buddhism, anti-Christianity, and the danka system, Harvard University Asia Center, 2007; pp. 1-30 (The Rise of Funerary Buddhism in Tokugawa Japan). [https://web.archive.org/web/20120331070517/http://www.fas.harvard.edu/~asiactr/publications/pdfs/Hur%20intro.pdf Internet archive]\n* [[Bernhard Scheid]], [https://web.archive.org/web/20150705145949/http://www.univie.ac.at/rel_jap/an/Geschichte/Terauke Inquisition unter buddhistischen Vorzeichen] {{in lang|de}} retrieved on March 20, 2008\n* Paul B. Watt, [https://web.archive.org/web/20120302110710/http://www.let.leidenuniv.nl/history/itinerario/bookreviews-16.html Review of \"Nam-Lin Hur, Death and Social Order in Tokugawa Japan: Buddhism, Anti-Christianity, and the Danka System\"] retrieved on March 20, 2008\n*{{cite book\n |last=Tamura\n |first=Yoshiro\n |title=Japanese Buddhism \u2013 A Cultural History\n |publisher=Kosei Publishing Company\n |location=Tokyo\n |year=2000 \n |edition=First\n |pages=232 pages\n |chapter=The Birth of the Japanese nation\n |isbn=4-333-01684-3\n }}\n* [http://law.hamline.edu/files/HeineRev.pdf Review of \"Death and Social Order in Tokugawa Japan: Buddhism, anti-Christianity and the Danka System\" by Nam-Lin Hur] By Steven Heine, retrieved on October 20, 2008\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* Tamamuro Fumio (2001), [https://web.archive.org/web/20110722073943/http://nirc.nanzan-u.ac.jp/publications/jjrs/pdf/611.pdf \"Local Society and the Temple-Parishioner Relationship within the Bakufu\u2019s Governance Structure\"], Japanese Journal of Religious Studies 28/3-4, 261\u201329\n* Tamamuro Fumio (2009), [https://web.archive.org/web/20151019211505/http://nirc.nanzan-u.ac.jp/nfile/2977 The Development of the Temple-Parishioner System], Japanese Journal of Religious Studies 36/1, 11\u201326\n\n[[Category:Japanese Buddhist terminology]]\n[[Category:Buddhism in Japan]]\n[[Category:Religious policy in Japan]]\n[[Category:Buddhism in the Edo period]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Danka_system"}
{"title_page": "Notre-Dame de Paris fire", "text_new": "{{short description|April 2019 fire at the cathedral of Notre-Dame de Paris, France}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox event\n| image                    = NotreDame20190415QuaideMontebello (cropped).jpg\n| image_upright            = 1.3\n| caption                  = Notre-Dame de Paris as seen from Quai de Montebello, {{nobr|with the spire aflame}}\n| map                      = {{location map|Paris#France|label=Notre-Dame Cathedral|lat_deg=48.8530|lon_deg=2.3498|float=center|width=250}}\n| time                     = 18:20 [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]] (16:20 [[UTC]])\n| duration                 = 15 hours<ref>{{cite news |title=Notre-Dame fire: Millions pledged to rebuild cathedral |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-47943705 |website=BBC News |accessdate=17 April 2019 |date=16 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416040109/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-47943705 |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n| date                     = {{start date and age|2019|04|15|df=y}}\n| venue                    = [[Notre-Dame Cathedral]]\n| location                 = Paris\n| coordinates              = {{coord|48.8530|N|2.3498|E|type:landmark_region:FR|display=title,inline}}\n| cause                    = Unknown\n| reported deaths          = 0<ref name=\"gutted\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/live-news/notre-dame-cathedral-fire-extinguished-paris-landmark-gutted-live-updates-04-16-2019/ |title=France vows to rebuild Notre Dame Cathedral after devastating fire |website=CBS News |date=17 April 2019 |accessdate=22 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416092503/https://www.cbsnews.com/live-news/notre-dame-cathedral-fire-extinguished-paris-landmark-gutted-live-updates-04-16-2019/ |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n| reported injuries        = 3<ref name=\"nytimes dontknow\">{{cite news |title=What We Know and Don't Know About the Notre-Dame Fire |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=15 April 2019 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/15/world/europe/notre-dame-fire-what-we-know.html |accessdate=21 July 2019 |url-access=limited}}</ref><ref name=\"cnbc1\" />\n| reported property damage = Roof and spire destroyed; windows and vaulted ceilings damaged\n}}\nOn 15 April 2019, just before 18:20 [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]], a [[structure fire]] broke out beneath the roof of [[Notre-Dame de Paris]] cathedral in Paris. By the time it was extinguished, the building's [[Fl\u00e8che|spire]] collapsed, and most of its roof had been destroyed and its upper walls severely damaged; extensive damage to the interior was prevented by its stone [[sexpartite vault|vaulted ceiling]], which largely contained the burning roof as it collapsed. Many works of art and religious relics were moved to safety early in the emergency, but others suffered some smoke damage, and some exterior art was damaged or destroyed. The cathedral's [[altar]], two [[pipe organ]]s, and its three 13th-century [[rose window]]s suffered little to no damage. Three emergency workers were injured. Contamination of the site and the nearby environment resulted.<ref name=plume>{{cite news|first1=Elian|last1=Peltier|first2=James|last2=Glanz|first3=Weiyi|last3=Cai|first4=Jeremy|last4=White|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/09/14/world/europe/notre-dame-fire-lead.html|title=Notre-Dame's Toxic Fallout|work=New York Times|date=14 September 2019|access-date=12 April 2020|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\nFrench president [[Emmanuel Macron]] said that the cathedral would be restored by 2024,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://apnews.com/4f3a963a52ae49fb824d38d55e01d1af |title=The Latest: Fire chaplain hailed as hero in Notre Dame blaze |date=17 April 2019 |website=AP News |language=en-US |access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref> and launched a fundraising campaign which brought in pledges of over \u20ac1{{nbsp}}billion {{as of|2019|04|22|lc=y}}. A complete restoration could require twenty years or more.\n\nOn 25 December 2019, the cathedral did not host Christmas services for the first time since the [[French Revolution]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2019/12/22/notre-dame-fire-no-christmas-mass-first-time-200-years/2726591001/ |title=Notre Dame Cathedral, ravaged by fire in April, will not host Christmas services for first time since French Revolution |last=Bacon |first=John |website=USA Today |language=en-US |access-date=2019-12-26}}</ref>\n{{toclimit|3}}\n\n== Background ==\nThe cathedral of Notre-Dame de Paris (\"Our Lady of Paris\"), part of the \"Paris, Banks of the Seine\" [[UNESCO World Heritage Site]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/600 |title=Paris, Banks of the Seine |publisher=[[United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization]] (UNESCO) |accessdate=16 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321014146/https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/600 |archive-date=21 March 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> was begun in the 12th century. Its walls and interior [[vaulted ceiling]] are of stone; its roof and [[fl\u00e8che]] (spire) were of wood (much of it 13th-century oak),<ref name=\"Monde16Avril\">{{cite news |url=https://www.lemonde.fr/les-decodeurs/article/2019/04/16/incendie-de-notre-dame-de-paris-ce-qui-a-ete-perdu-et-ce-qui-a-ete-sauve_5450988_4355770.html |title=Incendie de Notre-Dame de Paris: ce qui a \u00e9t\u00e9 perdu et ce qui a \u00e9t\u00e9 sauv\u00e9 |work=Le Monde |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] (AFP) |date=16 April 2019 |accessdate=16 April 2019 |language=fr |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416141316/https://www.lemonde.fr/les-decodeurs/article/2019/04/16/incendie-de-notre-dame-de-paris-ce-qui-a-ete-perdu-et-ce-qui-a-ete-sauve_5450988_4355770.html |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Sasuke |title=Notre-Dame de Paris: toute la charpente en feu, la fl\u00e8che effondr\u00e9e |url=http://maliactu.info/international/notre-dame-de-paris-toute-la-charpente-en-feu-la-fleche-effondree |work=Maliactu |date=15 April 2019 |language=fr |accessdate=16 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416180320/http://maliactu.info/international/notre-dame-de-paris-toute-la-charpente-en-feu-la-fleche-effondree |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> sheathed in lead<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/style/article/nortre-dame-fire-oak-wood-trnd/index.html |title=The entire wooden interior of Notre Dame Cathedral has been lost |first=Ryan |last=Pyror |date=15 April 2019 |accessdate=15 April 2019 |publisher=[[CNN]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415222810/https://www.cnn.com/style/article/nortre-dame-fire-oak-wood-trnd/index.html |archive-date=15 April 2019 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all}}</ref> to exclude water.\nThe spire was rebuilt several times, most recently in the 19th century.<ref>{{cite book |accessdate=18 April 2019 |first=Thomas |last=Okey |title=The Story of Paris |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MnlEAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA309& |page=308 |publisher=J.M. Dent & Compan |date=1919 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190420121400/https://books.google.com/books?id=MnlEAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA309& |archive-date=20 April 2019 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |accessdate=16 April 2019 |date=16 April 2019 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/04/16/story-behind-towering-notre-dame-spire-year-old-architect-commissioned-build-it/ |title=The story behind the towering Notre Dame spire and the 30-year-old architect commissioned to rebuild it |first=Meagan |last=Flynn |work=The Washington Post |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416120744/https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/04/16/story-behind-towering-notre-dame-spire-year-old-architect-commissioned-build-it/ |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe cathedral's stonework has been severely eroded by years of weather and pollution,<ref name=\"cbs undergoing\" /> and the spire had extensively rotted because fissures in its lead sheathing were admitting water.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/decades-of-neglect-threatened-notre-dame-well-before-it-burned-11555624252 |title=Decades of Neglect Threatened Notre Dame, Well Before It Burned |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=18 April 2019 |accessdate=18 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190418234833/https://www.wsj.com/articles/decades-of-neglect-threatened-notre-dame-well-before-it-burned-11555624252 |archive-date=18 April 2019 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The roof timbers were dry, spongy and powdery with age.<ref name=\"six_questions\" />\nIn 2014, the [[Ministry of Culture (France)|Ministry of Culture]] estimated needed renovations at \u20ac150{{nbsp}}million, and in 2016 the [[Archdiocese of Paris]] launched an appeal to raise \u20ac100{{nbsp}}million over the following five to ten years.\nAt the time of the fire, the spire was undergoing renovation<ref name=\"cbs undergoing\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/notre-dame-cathedral-fire-notre-dame-68-million-renovation-massive-fire-today/ |title=Notre Dame was undergoing $6.8&nbsp;million renovation when massive fire broke out |date=15 April 2019 |accessdate=15 April 2019 |website=[[CBS News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415194731/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/notre-dame-cathedral-fire-notre-dame-68-million-renovation-massive-fire-today/ |archive-date=15 April 2019 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Notre-Dame fire: Blaze breaks out amid renovations at 12th century cathedral |url=https://www.newcivilengineer.com/latest/notre-dame-fire-blaze-breaks-out-amid-renovations-at-12th-century-cathedral/10042011.article |website=New Civil Engineer |accessdate=16 April 2019 |date=15 April 2019 |first=Rob |last=Horgan |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416044826/https://www.newcivilengineer.com/latest/notre-dame-fire-blaze-breaks-out-amid-renovations-at-12th-century-cathedral/10042011.article |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Fire breaks out at top of Notre Dame Cathedral in Paris |url=https://www.independent.ie/world-news/fire-breaks-out-at-top-of-notre-dame-cathedral-in-paris-38017758.html |accessdate=16 April 2019 |work=The Irish Independent |date=15 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416035818/https://www.independent.ie/world-news/fire-breaks-out-at-top-of-notre-dame-cathedral-in-paris-38017758.html |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> and scaffolding had been erected over the [[transept]].<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ibtimes.com/notre-dame-cathedral-fire-photos-macron-vows-rebuild-670-year-old-church-2785632 |title=Notre Dame Cathedral Fire Photos: Macron Vows To Rebuild 670-Year Old Church |work=[[International Business Times]] |date=16 April 2019 |accessdate=16 April 2019 |first=Arthur |last=Villasanta |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416060753/https://www.ibtimes.com/notre-dame-cathedral-fire-photos-macron-vows-rebuild-670-year-old-church-2785632 |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nExtensive attention had been given to the risk of fire at the cathedral. The [[Paris Fire Brigade]] drilled regularly to prepare for emergencies there, including on-site exercises in 2018; a firefighter was posted to the cathedral each day; and [[fire warden]]s checked conditions beneath the roof three times daily.<ref name=\"forest\">{{cite news |last1=Breeden |first1=Aurelien |last2=Peltier |first2=Elian |last3=Alderman |first3=Liz |last4=P\u00e9rez-Pe\u00f1a |first4=Richard |title=Notre-Dame Attic Was Known as 'the Forest'. And It Burned Like One. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/16/world/europe/why-notre-dame-fire-spread.html |url-access=limited |work=The New York Times |date=16 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{Gallery\n| title        =Structural elements relevant to the fire\n|mode=packed\n| align        =\n| footer       =\n| style        =padding: 0;\n| state        =\n| height       =250\n| width        =\n| captionstyle =overflow: auto;\n| :File:Notre-Dame de Paris composite transverse section.svg\n | alt1=\n | Timber in reds, stone in blues. Left: tower, with framework and bells; centre (top to bottom, with [[Spire of Notre Dame de Paris|spire]] shown behind): lead roof, timber [[roof truss]]es, stone ceiling vault, nave; right: exterior walls and [[flying buttresses]]. ([[:Commons:File:Notre-Dame de Paris composite transverse section.svg|''Annotations]])\n| File:NOTRE DAME DE PARIS May 2012.jpg\n | alt2=\n | Interior of [[nave]] showing [[rib vault]]ing; in walls are [[clerestory]] windows (top), arches to [[triforium]] (middle), and arches to {{nobr|[[side aisle]]s}} (bottom).\n| File:20130214 - Notre-Dame de Paris - Les nouvelles cloches - 027.jpg\n | alt3=\n | Underside of rib vaulting, whose thrust outward onto the walls is countered by the inward thrust of the flying buttresses. Had the vaulting collapsed, the walls could have collapsed {{nobr|into the nave}}.\n| File:Charpentes Notre Dame 2018 6.jpg\n | alt4=\n | Timber roof framing; vaulted ceiling lies {{nobr|below walkways}}\n| File:\u5723\u6bcd\u9662\u697c\u9876.\u6d82\u9e262 - panoramio.jpg\n | alt5=\n | Lead roof sheathing\n| File:Notre-Dame (41443367785).jpg\n | alt6=\n | Roof and spire. The twelve [[Apostles]] statues at the spire's base had been removed for conservation days before the fire.\n}}\n\n== Fire ==\n[[File:Incendie Notre Dame de Paris cropped.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|From [[Square Ren\u00e9-Viviani]] at 19:51]]\nFire broke out in the attic beneath the cathedral's roof at 18:18.<ref name=\"nytimes 20190719\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/07/16/world/europe/notre-dame.html |title=Notre Dame came far closer to collapsing than people knew |first1=Elian |last1=Peltier |first2=James |last2=Glanz |first3=Mika |last3=Gr\u00f6ndahl |first4=Weiji |last4=Kai |first5=Adam |last5=Nossitr |first6=Liza |last6=Alderman |date=17 July 2019 |accessdate=17 July 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |url-access=limited}}</ref> At 18:20 the [[fire alarm]] sounded and guards evacuated the cathedral;<ref name=\"minutes\">{{cite news |last1=Hinnant |first1=Lori |title=66 minutes: The frantic race to save Notre Dame |url=https://apnews.com/e9cc2e0e2ce84b7a82abbc23e50bcea1 |work=AP News |date=17 April 2019 |accessdate=22 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416221902/https://apnews.com/e9cc2e0e2ce84b7a82abbc23e50bcea1 |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=live}} (archive copy legible if javascript turned off)</ref> a guard was sent to investigate, but to the wrong location{{snd}}the attic of the adjoining [[sacristy]]{{snd}}where he found no fire.  About fifteen minutes later the error was discovered, but by the time guards had climbed the three hundred steps to the cathedral attic the fire was well advanced.<ref name=\"nytimes 20190719\"/> The alarm system was not designed to automatically notify the fire brigade, which was summoned at 18:51 after the guards had returned.<ref name=\"nytimes20190419\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/19/world/europe/notre-dame-fire-safety.html |title=Notre-Dame's Safety Planners Underestimated the Risk, With Devastating Results |first=Katrin |last=Bennhold |first2=James |last2=Glanz |date=19 April 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=20 April 2019 |url-access=limited |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190420012938/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/19/world/europe/notre-dame-fire-safety.html |archive-date=20 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\nFirefighters arrived within ten minutes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-france-notredame-firefighters/paris-firefighters-got-on-notre-dame-site-in-less-than-10-minutes-idUSKCN1RT1N7 |first=Inti |last=Landauro |title=Paris firefighters got on Notre-Dame site in less than 10 minutes |work=Reuters |date=17 April 2017 |accessdate=23 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190418104848/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-france-notredame-firefighters/paris-firefighters-got-on-notre-dame-site-in-less-than-10-minutes-idUSKCN1RT1N7 |archive-date=18 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPolice evacuated the [[\u00cele de la Cit\u00e9]].<ref name=\"Nossiter\" /><ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-47941794 |title=Notre-Dame: Massive fire ravages Paris cathedral |date=16 April 2019 |website=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=22 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416192824/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-47941794 |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://elpais.com/internacional/2019/04/15/actualidad/1555348380_618268.html |title=La catedral de Notre Dame de Par\u00eds sufre un importante incendio |date=15 April 2019 |work=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |accessdate=15 April 2019 |language=es |issn=1134-6582 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415180838/https://elpais.com/internacional/2019/04/15/actualidad/1555348380_618268.html |archive-date=15 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> White smoke rising from the roof<ref name=\"Nossiter\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/15/world/europe/notre-dame-fire.html |title=Notre-Dame Cathedral in Paris Catches Fire |last=Nossiter |first=Adam |date=15 April 2019 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=15 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415174607/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/15/world/europe/notre-dame-fire.html |archive-date=15 April 2019 |url-status=live |last2=Breeden |first2=Aurelien |issn=0362-4331 |url-access=limited}}</ref> turned black before flames appeared from the spire, [[Backdraft|then turned yellow]].<ref name=\"Nossiter\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Massive fire engulfs beloved Notre Dame Cathedral in Paris |url=https://apnews.com/73404d09773740f699d4b92933abec50 |website=AP News |date=15 April 2019 |accessdate=16 April 2019 |first1=Lori |last1=Hinnant |first2=Samuel |last2=Petrequin |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415175914/https://apnews.com/73404d09773740f699d4b92933abec50 |archive-date=15 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Firefighting ===\n[[File:Fl\u00e8che en feu - Spire on Fire.jpeg|thumb|left|upright=0.65|The spire aflame]]\n[[File:NDonFire 8773 (edited).jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Firefighters using a [[deluge gun]]]]\nMore than 400 firefighters were engaged;<ref name=\"hard\" /> another hundred{{clarify|reason=firefighters or all people? sources contradictory?|date=July 2019}} worked to move precious objects to safety via [[Bucket brigade|a human chain]]<ref name=\"forest\" /> also including police and municipal workers.<ref name=\"reuters damage\" />\n\nThe fire was primarily fought from inside the structure, which was more dangerous for personnel but reduced potential damage to the cathedral; applying water from outside risked deflecting flames and hot gases (at temperatures up to 800{{nbsp}}\u00b0C or 1500{{nbsp}}\u00b0F) inwards.<ref name=\"six_questions\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leparisien.fr/faits-divers/six-questions-sur-l-incendie-de-notre-dame-de-paris-15-04-2019-8054094.php |title=Six questions sur l'incendie de Notre-Dame de Paris |trans-title=Six questions about the fire of Notre-Dame |website=Le Parisien |date=16 April 2019 |accessdate=16 April 2019 |language=fr |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416005330/http://www.leparisien.fr/faits-divers/six-questions-sur-l-incendie-de-notre-dame-de-paris-15-04-2019-8054094.php |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=live |first1=Jean-Michel |last1=D\u00e9cugis |first2=Vincent |last2=Gautronneau |first3=J\u00e9r\u00e9mie |last3=Pham-L\u00ea}}</ref> [[Deluge gun]]s<ref name=\"hard\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/15/europe/firefighters-notre-dame-intl/ |first=Joshua |last=Berlinger |title=Why the Notre Dame fire was so hard to put out |website=CNN |date=16 April 2019 |accessdate=24 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417103658/https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/15/europe/firefighters-notre-dame-intl/ |archive-date=17 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/world/live-news/notre-dame-fire/h_c29f6d43801da4f0b308b45e8665efe1 |title=400 firefighters mobilized for Notre Dame blaze |date=15 April 2019 |website=CNN |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newschannel5.com/news/world/notre-dame-cathedral-in-paris-is-on-fire-reports-say |title=Fire at Notre Dame Cathedral under control; firefighters have saved cathedral's towers |date=15 April 2019 |website=NewsChannel5 Nashville |accessdate=15 April 2019 |agency=CNN}}</ref> were used at lower-than-usual pressures to minimise damage to the cathedral and its contents.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-paris-firefighters-saved-notre-dame-11555540386 |url-access=subscription |title=How Paris Firefighters Helped Preserve Notre Dame Towers |first1=Sam |last1=Schechner |first2=Nick |last2=Kostov |date=17 April 2019 |work=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=18 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190418193228/https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-paris-firefighters-saved-notre-dame-11555540386 |archive-date=18 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\nWater was supplied by pump-boat from the [[Seine]].<ref name=\"forest\" /><!--Deliberate ambiguity, as some more recent sources seem to have only one pump-boat-->\n\n[[Aerial firefighting]] was not used because water dropped from heights could have done structural damage, and heated stone can crack if suddenly cooled.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2019/apr/15/notre-dame-cathedral-fire-paris-france-landmark-live-news |title=Cathedral fire under control after spire and roof destroyed \u2013 as it happened |work=The Guardian |accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=How Catastrophic Is the Notre-Dame Cathedral Fire? |url=https://www.citylab.com/design/2019/04/notre-dame-cathedral-fire-paris-gothic-architecture-history/587191/ |work=CityLab |date=15 April 2019 |first1=Kriston |last1=Capps |first2=Feargus |last2=O'Sullivan |accessdate=16 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416043321/https://www.citylab.com/design/2019/04/notre-dame-cathedral-fire-paris-gothic-architecture-history/587191/ |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Helicopters were not used because of dangerous [[updraft]]s<ref name=\"hard\" /> but drones were used for visual and [[thermal imaging]], and robots for visual imaging and directing water streams.<ref name=\"forest\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.techtimes.com/articles/241710/20190417/french-firefighting-robot-colossus-helped-save-burning-notre-dame-cathedral.htm |title=French Firefighting Robot Colossus Helped Save Burning Notre Dame Cathedral |last=Navarro |first=Alyssa |date=17 April 2019 |website=Tech Times |accessdate=17 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417162330/https://www.techtimes.com/articles/241710/20190417/french-firefighting-robot-colossus-helped-save-burning-notre-dame-cathedral.htm |archive-date=17 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Molten lead falling from the roof posed a special hazard for firefighters.<ref name=\"Nossiter\" />\n\nBy 18:52, smoke was visible from outside; flames appeared in the next ten minutes, as firefighters arrived. The spire of the cathedral collapsed at 19:50, creating a draft that slammed all the doors and sent a fireball through the attic. Firefighters then retreated from within the attic. Shortly before the spire fell, the fire had spread to the wooden framework inside the north tower, which supported [[Notre-Dame de Paris#Bells|eight very large bells]]. Had the bells fallen, it was thought that the damage done as they fell could have collapsed the towers, and with them the entire cathedral. At 20:30, firefighters abandoned attempts to extinguish the roof and concentrated on saving the towers, fighting from within and between the towers. By 21:45 the fire was under control.<ref name=\"nytimes 20190719\" />\n\nAdjacent apartment buildings were evacuated due to concern about possible collapse,<ref name=\"forest\" /> but on 19 April the fire brigade ruled out that risk.<ref name=\"april19rescue\">{{cite news |url=https://www.apnews.com/92db19558da04f09b94cc31fb5ce16a5 |title=Fire-ravaged Notre Dame now stabilized, firefighters leave |first1=Nicolas |last1=Vaux-Montagny |first2=Sylvie |last2=Corbet |website=AP News |date=19 April 2019 |accessdate=20 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190420011833/https://apnews.com/92db19558da04f09b94cc31fb5ce16a5 |archive-date=20 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> One firefighter and two police officers were injured.<ref name=\"nytimes dontknow\" /><ref name=\"cnbc1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/04/15/paris-notre-dame-cathedral-on-fire-reuters.html |title=Notre Dame will be rebuilt within the next five years, French President Emmanuel Macron says |last1=El-Bawab |first1=Nadine |last2=Newburger |first2=Emma |last3=Steinberg |first3=Marty |date=16 April 2019 |publisher=[[CNBC]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190418202153/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/04/15/paris-notre-dame-cathedral-on-fire-reuters.html |archive-date=18 April 2019 |url-status=live |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Damage ===\n{{further|Spire of Notre-Dame de Paris}}\n[[File:Notre-Dame-Fire.gif|thumb|right|upright=1.2|Animation showing the south facade before and after the fire; scaffolding had been erected as part of renovations underway when the fire started.]]\n[[File:Paris and environs with routes from London to Paris handbook for travellers (1913) eingenordet.png|thumb|upright=1.2|The area directly under the [[Crossing (architecture)|crossing]] and two other cells of vaulting collapsed]]\n[[File:Notre Dame de Paris roof damage aerial.webm|thumb|The roof reduced to piles of char atop the mostly intact vaults]]\nMost of the wood/metal roof and the spire of the cathedral was destroyed, with about one third of the roof remaining.<ref name=\"Nossiter\" /> The remnants of the roof and spire fell atop the stone vault underneath, which forms the ceiling of the cathedral's interior.<ref name=\"intact_vault\">{{cite web |last1=Lapin |first1=Tamar |title=Photos show center of Notre Dame cathedral miraculously intact |url=https://nypost.com/2019/04/15/photos-show-center-of-notre-dame-cathedral-miraculously-intact/ |website=New York Post |date=15 April 2019 |accessdate=16 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416032930/https://nypost.com/2019/04/15/photos-show-center-of-notre-dame-cathedral-miraculously-intact/ |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/style/article/nortre-dame-fire-oak-wood-trnd/index.html |title=The entire wooden interior of Notre Dame Cathedral has been destroyed |first=Ryan |last=Prior |date=15 April 2019 |website=CNN |accessdate=16 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415222810/https://www.cnn.com/style/article/nortre-dame-fire-oak-wood-trnd/index.html |archive-date=15 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Some sections of this vaulting collapsed in turn,<ref name=\"intact_vault\" /> allowing debris from the burning roof to fall to the marble floor below,<ref name=\"minutes\" /> but most sections remained intact due to the use of [[rib vault]]ing, greatly reducing damage to the cathedral's interior and objects within.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/opinion/op-ed/la-oe-goodheart-notre-dame-fire-gothic-20190417-story.html |first=Adam |last=Goodheart |title=Who saved Notre Dame? Its builders |date=17 April 2019 |work=Los Angeles Times |department=Op-Ed |accessdate=23 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423213709/https://www.latimes.com/opinion/op-ed/la-oe-goodheart-notre-dame-fire-gothic-20190417-story.html |archive-date=23 April 2019 |url-status=live |url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\nThe cathedral contained a large number of artworks, religious relics, and other irreplaceable treasures,<ref name=\"contents\" /> including a [[Crown of thorns#France|crown of thorns]] said to be the one Jesus wore at his crucifixion, a purported [[True Cross|piece of the cross]] on which Jesus was crucified, the [[Louis IX of France#Religious nature|Tunic of St. Louis]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Notre Dame crown of thorns and St Louis tunic saved from cathedral fire |url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/04/16/notre-dame-crown-thorns-st-louis-tunic-saved-cathedral-fire-9219579/ |newspaper=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |date=16 April 2019 |accessdate=16 April 2019 |df=dmy-all |first=Richard |last=Hartley-Parkinson |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416135729/https://metro.co.uk/2019/04/16/notre-dame-crown-thorns-st-louis-tunic-saved-cathedral-fire-9219579/ |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Buncombe\" /> a [[Notre-Dame de Paris#Organ|much-rebuilt]] pipe organ by [[Aristide Cavaill\u00e9-Coll]], and the 14th-century [[Virgin of Paris]] statue.<ref name=\"contents\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/art-destroyed-in-fire-notre-dame-paris-artifacts-13769096.php |title=What's inside the Notre Dame Cathedral in Paris |last=Martichoux |first=Alix |date=15 April 2019 |website=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=15 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415211841/https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/art-destroyed-in-fire-notre-dame-paris-artifacts-13769096.php |archive-date=15 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSome artwork had been removed in preparation for the renovations, and most of the cathedral's sacred relics were held in the adjoining sacristy, which the fire did not reach; all the cathedral's relics survived.<ref name=\"april19rescue\" /><ref>{{cite web |first=Thomas |last=Adamson |url=http://www.startribune.com/drunk-on-smoke-notre-dame-s-bees-survive-cathedral-blaze/508801942/ |title=Drunk on smoke: Notre Dame's bees survive cathedral blaze |work=[[Star Tribune]] |agency=Associated Press |date=19 April 2019 |accessdate=19 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190419144702/http://www.startribune.com/drunk-on-smoke-notre-dame-s-bees-survive-cathedral-blaze/508801942/ |archive-date=19 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/pariss-notre-cathedral-is-on-fire/2019/04/15/c487906e-5fa1-11e9-bf24-db4b9fb62aa2_story.html |title=Notre Dame Cathedral spire collapses as Paris monument is consumed by fire |last1=McAuley |first1=James |last2=Whitt |first2=Griff |date=15 April 2019 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415184931/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/pariss-notre-cathedral-is-on-fire/2019/04/15/c487906e-5fa1-11e9-bf24-db4b9fb62aa2_story.html |archive-date=15 April 2019 |url-status=live |accessdate=15 April 2019 |url-access=limited}}</ref> Some contents were moved by a human chain of emergency workers and civil servants.<ref name=\"reuters damage\" /> Many valuables that were not removed also survived, but the state of many others remained unknown as of 16 April.<ref name=\"Monde16Avril\" />{{Update inline|date=March 2020}}\n\n[[came|Lead joints]] in some of the 19th-century stained-glass windows melted,<ref name=\"nytimes cot\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/15/world/europe/crown-of-thorns-notre-dame.html |title=Notre-Dame: Fate of Priceless Cultural Treasures Uncertain |last=Marshall |first=Alex |date=15 April 2019 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=16 April 2019 |last2=Stack |first2=Liam |issn=0362-4331 |last3=Murphy |first3=Heather |url-access=limited |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416070310/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/15/world/europe/crown-of-thorns-notre-dame.html |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> but the three major rose windows, dating to the 13th century, were undamaged. One weakened window may need to be dismantled for safekeeping.{{update inline|date=June 2019}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Guyonnet |first1=Paul |title=Notre-Dame: Les vitraux des rosaces ont surv\u00e9cu \u00e0 l'incendie |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.fr/entry/notre-dame-vitraux-rosaces-incendie_fr_5cb58dece4b082aab08b55e0 |accessdate=16 April 2019 |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |location=Notre-Dame |date=16 April 2019 |language=fr |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416123535/https://www.huffingtonpost.fr/entry/notre-dame-vitraux-rosaces-incendie_fr_5cb58dece4b082aab08b55e0 |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newsweek.com/notre-dame-rose-windows-fire-paris-cathedral-1397773 |title=Notre Dame 'miracle'? Rose windows' stained glass appears to have survived savage blaze |first=Katherine |last=Hignett |date=16 April 2019 |website=[[Newsweek]] |accessdate=17 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416143859/https://www.newsweek.com/notre-dame-rose-windows-fire-paris-cathedral-1397773 |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-france-notredame-patrimony-idUSKCN1RS1IF |work=Reuters |title=Notre-Dame's famed rose window spared but blaze harms priceless artworks |first1=Sarah |last1=White |first2=Elizabeth |last2=Pineau |date=16 April 2019 |accessdate=17 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416221222/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-france-notredame-patrimony-idUSKCN1RS1IF |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Several pews were destroyed and the [[Vault (architecture)|vaulted arches]] were blackened by smoke, though the church's main cross and altar survived, along with the statues surrounding it.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thelocal.fr/20190416/like-a-nightmare-hundreds-of-parisians-gather-to-witness-destruction-at-notre-dame |title='The church is burning and the whole world is crying' \u2013 Parisians mourn for Notre-Dame |work=[[The Local]] |date=16 April 2019 |accessdate=20 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417135343/https://www.thelocal.fr/20190416/like-a-nightmare-hundreds-of-parisians-gather-to-witness-destruction-at-notre-dame |archive-date=17 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/notre-dame-counts-cost-daylight-reveals-damage-092808310.html |title=Notre-Dame counts cost as daylight reveals damage |work=Yahoo! News |agency=Agence France-Presse (AFP) |date=16 April 2019 |accessdate=16 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416190208/https://news.yahoo.com/notre-dame-counts-cost-daylight-reveals-damage-092808310.html |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSome paintings, apparently only smoke-damaged,<ref name=\"nytimes cot\"/> are expected to be transported to the [[Louvre]] for restoration. A number of statues, including those of the twelve Apostles at the base of the spire, had been removed in preparation for renovations.<ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/notre-dame-cathedral-paris-fire-1.5098604 |title=Notre-Dame Cathedral spire in Paris collapses, engulfed in flames |agency=[[Reuters]] |publisher=[[CBC News]] |date=15 April 2019 |accessdate=15 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415181728/https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/notre-dame-cathedral-paris-fire-1.5098604 |archive-date=15 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Buncombe\">{{cite news |last1=Buncombe |first1=Andrew |title=Notre Dame's historic statues safe after being removed just days before massive fire |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/notre-dame-cathedral-fire-statues-renovation-apostles-evangelists-a8871586.html |accessdate=15 April 2019 |work=The Independent |date=15 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415195451/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/notre-dame-cathedral-fire-statues-renovation-apostles-evangelists-a8871586.html |archive-date=15 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\nThe rooster-shaped [[reliquary]] atop the spire was found damaged but intact among the debris.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rtl.fr/actu/justice-faits-divers/le-coq-de-la-fleche-de-notre-dame-de-paris-retrouve-7797444660 |title=Le coq de la fl\u00e8che a \u00e9t\u00e9 retrouv\u00e9 |website=RTL |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] (AFP) |language=fr |first=Thomas |last=Pierre |date=16 April 2019 |accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref>\nThe three pipe organs were not significantly damaged.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.europe1.fr/societe/exclusif-lorgue-principal-de-notre-dame-de-paris-miraculeusement-preserve-rien-na-brule-rien-na-fondu-3892910 |title=L'orgue principal de Notre-Dame de Paris miraculeusement pr\u00e9serv\u00e9 |date=16 April 2019 |publisher=[[Europe 1]] |accessdate=16 April 2019 |language=fr |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416094748/https://www.europe1.fr/societe/exclusif-lorgue-principal-de-notre-dame-de-paris-miraculeusement-preserve-rien-na-brule-rien-na-fondu-3892910 |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/24/arts/music/notre-dame-organ-fire.html |title=Notre-Dame Musicians Rejoice That Cathedral's Organ Was Spared |last=Marshall |first=Alex |date=24 April 2019 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=24 April 2019 |issn=0362-4331 |url-access=limited}}</ref> The largest of the cathedral's bells, the [[Bourdon (bell)|bourdon]], was not damaged.<ref name=\"Monde16Avril\" /> The liturgical treasury of the cathedral and the \"grands [[May (painting)|Mays]]\" paintings were moved to safety.<ref name=\"Monde16Avril\" />\n\n==== Environmental damage ====\n[[Airparif]] said winds rapidly dispersed the smoke, carrying it away aloft along the Seine corridor. It did not find elevated levels of particulate air pollution at monitoring stations nearby.<ref>{{cite web |title=Incendie de Notre-Dame de Paris: point sur la situation |url=https://www.paris.fr/notre-dame |website=paris.fr |language=fr |accessdate=20 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190420192759/https://www.paris.fr/notre-dame |archive-date=20 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Incendie de Notre-Dame : le feu a-t-il pollu\u00e9 l\u2019air de Paris ? |url=http://www.leparisien.fr/societe/incendie-de-notre-dame-le-feu-a-t-il-pollue-l-air-de-paris-16-04-2019-8054682.php |website=leparisien.fr |language=fr-FR |date=16 April 2019}}</ref> The Paris police have stated that there was no danger from breathing the air around the fire.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chrisafis |first1=Angelique |title=Notre Dame fire: police say air not toxic despite high lead levels on ground |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/may/09/paris-police-say-no-danger-of-toxic-inhalation-from-air-near-notre-dame |website=The Guardian |date=9 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe burned-down roof was covered with over 400 metric [[tons]] of [[lead (metal)|lead]].<ref name=plume/><!--the NYT seriously did not specify what sort of 460 tons--><ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://time.com/5638584/notre-dame-lead-poisoning/ |author=Billy Perrigo |title=Notre Dame Fire: Environmental Group Files Lead Poisoning Lawsuit |magazine=Time |date=30 July 2019 |accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref> Settling dust substantially raised surface lead levels in some places nearby,<ref>{{cite web |title=Blood tests recommended over Notre Dame lead risk |url=https://apnews.com/33a616f0a5d844578b425d806f4fb362 |website=AP NEWS |accessdate=7 August 2019 |date=4 June 2019}}</ref> notably the cordoned-off area and places left open during the fire.<ref>{{cite web |title=Information aux riverains et aux personnes travaillant aux abords de la cath\u00e9drale Notre-Dame de Paris |url=http://www.prefectures-regions.gouv.fr/ile-de-france/content/download/57788/379997/file/CP%20PP%2027042019%20-%20Information%20aux%20riverains%20de%20Notre-Dame.pdf |website=[prefectures-regions.gouv.fr/ile-de-france Prefecture of Paris website] |publisher=[[Prefecture of Paris]] |date=27 April 2019}}</ref> Wet cleaning for surfaces<ref>{{cite web |title=Officials warn of lead pollution risks after Notre-Dame blaze |url=https://phys.org/news/2019-05-notre-dame-roof-astronomical.html |website=phys.org |language=en-us |date=9 May 2019}}</ref> and blood tests for children and pregnant women were recommended in the immediate area.<ref>{{cite web |last1=France-Presse |first1=Agence |title=Children and pregnant women around Notre Dame warned over lead |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jun/04/notre-dame-lead-levels-in-blood |website=The Guardian |date=4 June 2019}}</ref> People working on the cathedral after the fire did not initially take the lead precautions required for their own protection; materials leaving the site were decontaminated, but some clothing was not, and some precautions were not correctly followed; as a result, the worksite failed some inspections and was temporarily shut down.<ref name=plume/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kovacs |first1=St\u00e9phane |title=Notre-Dame de Paris : le chantier suspendu \u00e0 cause du plomb |url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/actualite-france/le-chantier-de-notre-dame-suspendu-pour-plusieurs-jours-par-mesure-de-precaution-20190725 |website=Le Figaro |date=25 July 2019}}</ref> There was also more widespread contamination; testing, cleanup, and public health advisories were delayed for months, and the neighbourhood was not decontaminated for four months, prompting widespread criticism.<ref name=plume/>\n\nAverage lead levels in Paris streets are normally five times the indoor legal limit (1000 [[microgram|\u03bcg]]/m<sup>2</sup>), due to historic uses of lead,<ref>{{cite news |title=The Notre Dame Fire Spread Toxic Lead Dust Over Paris |url=https://www.wired.com/story/the-notre-dame-fire-spread-toxic-lead-dust-over-paris/ |website=Wired |date=1 August 2019 |accessdate=3 August 2019 |last1=O'Sullivan |first1=Feargus}}</ref> principally from runoff from intact roofs.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Robert |first1=Pauline |last2=Gromaire |first2=Marie-Christine |last3=de Gouvello |first3=Bernard |last4=Chebbo |first4=Ghassan |title=IMPACT DES MAT\u00c9RIAUX DE TOITURES SUR LA CONTAMINATION M\u00c9TALLIQUE DES EAUX DE RUISSELLEMENT URBAINES |conference=17\u00e8mes Journ\u00e9es Scientifiques de l\u2019Environnement: le citoyen, la ville et l\u2019environnement |date=May 2006 |url=https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-00182628/document}}</ref> The Health Ministry rules that children should not be exposed to more than 70 micrograms/m<sup>2</sup> indoors. There is no legal limit for outdoor lead levels, which are often very heterogeneous; the L'Agence r\u00e9gionale de sant\u00e9 (ARS) d'Ile-de-France is not certain if some of the elevated levels being measured are connected to the fire.<ref>{{cite web |title=Plomb de Notre-Dame: l'Agence r\u00e9gionale de sant\u00e9 se veut rassurante |url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/plomb-de-notre-dame-l-agence-regionale-de-sante-se-veut-rassurante-20190704 |website=Le Figaro |date=4 July 2019 |agency=AFP}}</ref> This lack of clarity and threshold-linked mandatory measures may have delayed action. In mid-July, regional health officials raised their outdoor guideline from 1000 [[micrograms]]/m<sup>2</sup> to 5000.<ref name=plume/><!--93 to 464 \"micrograms per square foot\", but 70mcg/m2 limit given in original metric units. The NYT is apparently making the transition to metric units gradually...--> Rain can redistribute the lead dust.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Willsher |first1=Kim |title=Notre Dame firefighters should be tested for lead, say campaigners |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/may/10/notre-dame-firefighters-should-be-tested-for-lead-say-campaigners |website=The Guardian |date=10 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Reactions ===\n[[File:Hommage_sauveteurs_ND2.jpg|thumb|upleft=1.2|left|Plaque in front of the [[H\u00f4tel de Ville, Paris|H\u00f4tel de Ville]] in homage to the cathedral and those who helped save it]]<!-- not sure this is needed; if so, it should probably be cropped to the billboard, not the statue-->\nMacron, postponing a speech to address the [[yellow vests movement]] planned for that evening,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://apnews.com/e4f5f49d9f2d46348cdda1d86ea8a41e |title=France's Macron requests post-fire pause from politics |website=AP News |date=16 April 2019 |accessdate=23 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423215533/https://apnews.com/e4f5f49d9f2d46348cdda1d86ea8a41e |archive-date=23 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> went to Notre Dame and gave a brief address there.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/macron-postpones-speech-after-notre-dame-fire/ |title=Notre Dame fire 'fully extinguished' as fundraising starts |first1=Rym |last1=Momtaz |first2=Laurenz |last2=Gehrke |date=16 April 2019 |website=[[Politico]] |accessdate=23 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190420085901/https://www.politico.eu/article/macron-postpones-speech-after-notre-dame-fire/ |archive-date=20 April 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Numerous world religious{{efn|The [[Holy See|Vatican]],<ref name=\"ap-latest\" /> and the Presiding Bishop of [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thechurchnews.com/global/2019-04-15/notre-dame-fire-flames-paris-holy-week-hope-jesus-christ-49533 |title=Hope from ashes: Why the Notre Dame fire is a symbol of rebirth during Holy Week |date=15 April 2019 |first=Aubrey |last=Eyre |work=[[Church News]] |accessdate=16 April 2019 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.o